  "name": "Morrison COU2 — VAD hemolysis credibility assessment (W-AR-05 adversarial sample)",
  "description": "Synthetic adversarial UoA for ASME V&V 40 weakness detection. COU2 evaluates CFD hemolysis prediction for a Class III VAD device at Model Risk Level 5. A validation result is present and narratively references a comparator dataset (FDA benchmark steady-state pump data), but the comparedAgainst link is absent from the result object — triggering W-AR-05. Additionally, the referenced comparator was collected under steady-state, constant-flow conditions, whereas the declared COU requires pulsatile flow across five flow-speed combinations. This comparator-COU mismatch constitutes an undercutting defeater (D3): the inference from validation evidence to COU applicability is undermined because the experimental regime differs fundamentally from the intended use regime. The package is structurally complete and plausible on quick read; the flaw is embedded in the validation result block.",
  "bindsRequirement": "https://uofa.net/synth/req/cou2-hemolysis-absolute-threshold",
  "bindsClaim": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/cou2-cfd-hemolysis-below-clinical-threshold",
  "bindsModel": "https://uofa.net/synth/model/cfd-hemolysis-centrifugal-pump-v3",
  "bindsDataset": [
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-generic-pump-steady-state-benchmark",
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/monte-carlo-uq-hemolysis-predictions"
  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to predict absolute hemolysis levels across operating conditions for a centrifugal blood pump used as a ventricular assist device (VAD). Model influence is HIGH (model is primary basis for hemolysis acceptance); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect prediction could result in chronic patient hemolysis requiring clinical intervention). Model Risk Level 5 — the highest in the Morrison assessment.",
    "deviceClass": "Class III",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou2-vad",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to predict absolute hemolysis index values for a Class III VAD device across 5 flow-speed combinations. Results must demonstrate hemolysis below absolute clinical threshold (not relative to predicate). Requires Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification on hemolysis predictions.",
    "modelInfluence": "High",
    "name": "COU2: Ventricular assist device use (Class III)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/no-comparator",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Steady-state FDA benchmark comparison — comparator link absent",
      "description": "The CFD hemolysis model was compared against the FDA generic centrifugal pump benchmark dataset (Stewart et al., 2012), which was collected under steady-state, constant-flow conditions at five fixed operating points. Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values agreed with benchmark measurements to within 18% across all operating points, which the assessment team characterised as acceptable agreement. However, the declared COU requires pulsatile flow simulation across five flow-speed combinations representative of VAD operating envelopes; the FDA benchmark dataset contains no pulsatile flow measurements. The inference that steady-state validation evidence supports pulsatile COU applicability is therefore undercut: the flow regime assumed by the comparator is categorically different from the flow regime in which the model will be used clinically. Despite this regime mismatch being acknowledged in the narrative, no formal comparedAgainst link to the benchmark dataset or experimental protocol is recorded in this result object, and no supplemental pulsatile validation dataset has been identified to close the gap."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/uq-coverage-check",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Monte Carlo UQ coverage validation against in-vitro hemolysis spread",
      "description": "Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification was performed across rheological and geometric input parameters. The 95th-percentile prediction interval for NIH was compared against the inter-device variability reported in the FDA benchmark dataset to assess whether UQ coverage was adequate. The prediction interval encompassed 91% of experimental observations, marginally below the 95% coverage target specified for MRL 5.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-generic-pump-steady-state-benchmark"
    }
  ],
